<!-- Setoku ClickHouse system-log policy: disable the chatty ones, TTL the rest.

     ClickHouse's own telemetry tables (system.*_log) are UNBOUNDED by default and,
     on a busy box, outgrow the actual lake data many times over (observed
     ~160 MB/day of telemetry vs ~14 MB/day of real ingest). They are rebuildable
     server diagnostics, NOT user data (I4).

     TWO different problems, two different fixes:

     (a) DISK — a rolling 14-day TTL caps size (and, for trace_log, trace-off.xml
         disables the profilers that feed it so it stays empty).

     (b) STEADY CPU/IO — a TTL only deletes OLD rows; it does nothing about the
         constant WRITES + background merges. metric_log and
         asynchronous_metric_log flush ~every second, and text_log mirrors every
         server log line (already in stdout/docker logs) — on a small shared box
         (2 vCPU) that is continuous overhead, and nothing here reads them (no
         server-side dashboards; I8). So DISABLE those three outright:
         `remove="1"` deletes the shipped-default section, so the log is never
         started (the standard ClickHouse disable). The useful low-rate logs
         (query_log for the audit trail, the profile/part logs) stay, TTL-capped.

     Mounted at /etc/clickhouse-server/config.d/ with a zz- prefix (applied last,
     so these override ClickHouse's defaults). Applies on (re)start. Existing rows
     in the now-disabled tables are cleared separately (a one-time TRUNCATE on
     deploy, or they age out under the TTL they previously carried). -->
<clickhouse>
    <!-- disabled: high-frequency, low-value telemetry nobody here reads -->
    <asynchronous_metric_log remove="1"/>
    <metric_log remove="1"/>
    <text_log remove="1"/>

    <!-- kept, but capped at 14 days (plenty for post-incident debugging) -->
    <query_log><ttl>event_date + INTERVAL 14 DAY DELETE</ttl></query_log>
    <query_thread_log><ttl>event_date + INTERVAL 14 DAY DELETE</ttl></query_thread_log>
    <trace_log><ttl>event_date + INTERVAL 14 DAY DELETE</ttl></trace_log>
    <processors_profile_log><ttl>event_date + INTERVAL 14 DAY DELETE</ttl></processors_profile_log>
    <part_log><ttl>event_date + INTERVAL 14 DAY DELETE</ttl></part_log>
</clickhouse>
